bly say =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D or perhaps =0A=E2=80=9Csure we=E2=80=99ll giv=
e you some stock if you give us money for it.=E2=80=9D Stock is =0Avaluable=
, the company can sell it for money, it=E2=80=99s the way the company gets =
=0Afinancing, and just giving you some of it for free will dilute all of it=
s other =0Ashareholders.=0A=0AAnother thing you could do is email the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s transfer agent and ask it to =0Agive you some of the company=
=E2=80=99s stock. The transfer agent is the company in =0Acharge of keeping=
 the records of how much stock the company has and who owns =0Ait, and so i=
n some quite real sense thetransfer agent can also just make up the =0Acomp=
any=E2=80=99s stock: If the transfer agent says that you have 100 shares of=
 the =0Astock, then in most practical senses you really do.=0A=0ATo be clea=
r, the transfer agent will also probably say =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D: It=E2=80=
=99s not supposed =0Ato just make up stock in its client companies, and if =
it does that it will =0Agenerally get in bad trouble. Transfer agents arere=
gulated by the US Securities =0Aand Exchange Commission =0A<https://www.sec=
.gov/about/divisions-offices/division-trading-markets/transfer-agents>=0A,=
 and their whole business is about keepingaccurate track of the stock. And =
yet =0Athe incentives are different. The company has only the one stock, it=
s =0Aexecutives=E2=80=99 wealth is largely in that stock, it cares a lot ab=
out its stock =0Aprice and ownership. The transfer agent keeps track of lot=
s and lots of stocks, =0Agenerally for modest fees. It just doesn=E2=80=99t=
 care allthat much about any =0Aparticular stock. Maybe it will make a mist=
ake and send you some stock=3F=0A=0AI mean, mostly not. But sometimes! We t=
alked last month =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-07-01/=
