 about a company called Canna-Global Acquisition Corp., which =E2=80=A6 the=
 facts are =0Adisputed, but one version of the story is roughly that a guy =
bamboozled the =0Acompany=E2=80=99s transfer agent into giving him a few mi=
llion dollars=E2=80=99 worth of the =0Acompany=E2=80=99s stock, which he pr=
omptly sold. This was embarrassing for everyone, =0Anot least the transfer =
agent, which quickly agreed to compensate the company =0Afor the missing sh=
ares.=0A=0AOr here=E2=80=99s an SEC enforcement action =0A<https://www.sec.=
gov/newsroom/press-releases/2024-101> from last week against =0AEquiniti Tr=
ust Company LLC (formerly American Stock Transfer & Trust Company =0ALLC), =
a transfer agent that was not absolutely 100% reliable about not issuing =
=0Afree shares to people who emailed and asked. Fromthe SEC=E2=80=99s order=
 =0A<https://www.sec.gov/files/litigation/admin/2024/34-100780.pdf>:=0A=0AI=
n September 2022, an unknown threat actor outside of Respondent joined an =
=0Aexisting email chain that included the client contact at a U.S.-based =
=0Apublic-issuer client of Respondent (the =E2=80=9CIssuer=E2=80=9D), the I=
ssuer=E2=80=99s relationship =0Amanager at Respondent, and an external fina=
ncial management adviser to the =0AIssuer. Pretending to be the Issuer=E2=
=80=99s employee, the threat actor instructed =0ARespondent to issue millio=
ns of new shares of the Issuer, liquidate those =0Ashares, and send the pro=
ceeds to bank accounts located in Hong Kong. The threat =0Aactor concealed =
its identity by using an email domain that was almost identical =0Ato the r=
eal Issuer=E2=80=99s domain except for one letter, by imitating closely the=
 =0Averbal patterns and practices of the existing contact at the Issuer, an=
d by =0Asending its instructions as a continuation of the existing email ch=
ain rather =0Athan as a new stand-alone request. The relationship manager a=
t Respondent, who =0Adid not notice the altered email address used by the t=
hreat actor, did not take =0Asteps beyond replying to the email chain to ve=
rify that the Issuer did in fact =0Awant to issue and liquidate new shares =
and then transfer the proceeds to a =0Aforeign bank.=0A=0AOver the course o=
f a month, at the direction of what appeared to be the Issuer =0Abut was ac=
tually the threat actor, Respondent issued approximately 5.3 million =0Asha=
res of the Issuer and then instructed a third-party broker-dealer to sell =
=0Aapproximately 3.3 million of those new shares for about $4.78 million. =
=0ARespondent transferred all the proceeds to Hong Kong-based bank accounts=
.=0A=0AThe Issuer eventually noticed in November 2022 that the number of i=
ts shares =0Aoutstanding in the market was greater than reflected in its in=
ternal records. =0AThe Issuer alerted Respondent, which investigated and th=
en discovered the fraud =0Aand took action to claw back the funds that had =
been sent to Hong Kong. =0AUltimately, Respondent was able to recover appro=
ximately $1 million and fully =0Areimbursed the Issuer for the money lost a=
s a result of the issuance and sale =0Aof the shares.=0A=0ASo there is some=
 precedent for the =E2=80=9Chack the transfer agent=E2=80=9D approach to wo=
